<item>
            <title>[HIVE-23704] Thrift HTTP Server Does Not Handle Auth Handle Correctly</title>
                <link>https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/HIVE-23704</link>
                <project id="12310843" key="HIVE">Hive</project>
                    <description>&lt;div class=&quot;code panel&quot; style=&quot;border-width: 1px;&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;codeHeader panelHeader&quot; style=&quot;border-bottom-width: 1px;&quot;&gt;&lt;b&gt;ThriftHttpServlet.java&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;codeContent panelContent&quot;&gt;
&lt;pre class=&quot;code-java&quot;&gt;
  &lt;span class=&quot;code-keyword&quot;&gt;private&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class=&quot;code-object&quot;&gt;String&lt;/span&gt;[] getAuthHeaderTokens(HttpServletRequest request,
      &lt;span class=&quot;code-object&quot;&gt;String&lt;/span&gt; authType) &lt;span class=&quot;code-keyword&quot;&gt;throws&lt;/span&gt; HttpAuthenticationException {
    &lt;span class=&quot;code-object&quot;&gt;String&lt;/span&gt; authHeaderBase64 = getAuthHeader(request, authType);
    &lt;span class=&quot;code-object&quot;&gt;String&lt;/span&gt; authHeaderString = StringUtils.newStringUtf8(
        Base64.decodeBase64(authHeaderBase64.getBytes()));
    &lt;span class=&quot;code-object&quot;&gt;String&lt;/span&gt;[] creds = authHeaderString.split(&lt;span class=&quot;code-quote&quot;&gt;&quot;:&quot;&lt;/span&gt;);
    &lt;span class=&quot;code-keyword&quot;&gt;return&lt;/span&gt; creds;
  }
&lt;/pre&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So here, it takes the authHeaderBase64 (which is a base-64 string), and converts it into bytes, and then it tries to decode those bytes.  That is incorrect   It should covert base-64 string directly into bytes.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I tried to do this as part of &lt;a href=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/HIVE-22676&quot; title=&quot;Replace Base64 in hive-service Package&quot; class=&quot;issue-link&quot; data-issue-key=&quot;HIVE-22676&quot;&gt;&lt;del&gt;HIVE-22676&lt;/del&gt;&lt;/a&gt; and the tests was failing because the string that is being decoded is not actually Base-64 (see attached image)  It has a stray space and a colon.  Again, the existing code doesn&apos;t care because it&apos;s not parsing Base-64 text, it is parsing the bytes generated by converting base-64 text to bytes.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I&apos;m not sure what affect this has, what security issues this may present, but it&apos;s definitely not correct.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
